<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/818CD6C9-61EE-41F2-9F37-0C7A8F43E25D"><gtr:id>818CD6C9-61EE-41F2-9F37-0C7A8F43E25D</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Birmingham</gtr:name><gtr:department>School of Psychology</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Edgbaston Park Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Edgbaston</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>B15 2TT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>West Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/818CD6C9-61EE-41F2-9F37-0C7A8F43E25D"><gtr:id>818CD6C9-61EE-41F2-9F37-0C7A8F43E25D</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Birmingham</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Edgbaston Park Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Edgbaston</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>B15 2TT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>West Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/0EC3104E-E220-4F6B-A1CC-CF1A11228C41"><gtr:id>0EC3104E-E220-4F6B-A1CC-CF1A11228C41</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Pia</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Rotshtein</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE004237%2F1"><gtr:id>5FD4EA0B-BBCD-4379-A955-E0ADFA813A24</gtr:id><gtr:title>How do fearful eyes and happy smiles affect perception?</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E004237/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Recent behaviour studies demonstrate that the eyes convey the most crucial information for recognizing fearful expressions while happy expressions are detected by relying on information from the mouth (Smith et al., 2005, Ps&lt;em>ychol. Sci.). &lt;/em>Intriguingly it has been shown that patients and healthy subjects who fail to look at the eyes also show deficit in recognizing fearful expressions, typically these subjects would also show an abnormal amygdala function (Adolphs et al., 2005, &lt;em>Nature;&lt;/em> Corden et al., 2006, JoCN). In line with the above claims, using fMRI it was demonstrated that amygdala is particularly sensitive to information from fearful eyes (Morris et al., 2002, &lt;em>Neuroimage;&lt;/em> Whalen et al., 2004, Science). &lt;br />&lt;br />The aim of the project is to investigate the neural network that mediates the significance of the eyes in fearful expressions and of the mouth in happy expressions. Specifically, we will investigate the effects different expressions have on attention to different features of a face. We hypothesis that effects of expressions on attention are mediated in a network of regions that include: early visual regions, superior temporal sulcus, intraparietal sulcus and amygdala amongst other. Using dynamic causal modeling and model comparison tools for fMRI analysis we will investigate the connection structures between these regions.&lt;/p> 
